---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const posts = [
  {
    date: 'Apr 04, 2026',
    tag: 'Type 1',
    title: 'The two-day rule for T1D and exercise.',
    body:
      'A single bout of training writes glucose dynamics into the next 24–48 hours. What that means for programming, dosing, and how to think about a hard hike on a Saturday.',
    read: '8 min',
  },
  {
    date: 'Mar 17, 2026',
    tag: 'Hiking',
    title: 'How I trained for the Pemi Loop.',
    body:
      'A twelve-week block built around eccentric loading, Zone 2, and the unglamorous work of teaching ankles to listen to talus.',
    read: '11 min',
  },
  {
    date: 'Feb 22, 2026',
    tag: 'Recovery',
    title: 'Sleep is the program.',
    body:
      'The CHEK Dr. Quiet framing meets the modern recovery literature. Why a single short night costs more than most people think — and what to do about it during a heavy training block.',
    read: '7 min',
  },
  {
    date: 'Jan 30, 2026',
    tag: 'Methodology',
    title: 'Reading the 2026 ACSM position stand without losing the plot.',
    body:
      '137 systematic reviews. 30,000 participants. Six things actually changed about how I program for adults — and several things didn\'t.',
    read: '9 min',
  },
  {
    date: 'Dec 18, 2025',
    tag: 'Hiking',
    title: 'A descent is its own training problem.',
    body:
      'Coming down off Mt. Washington is the part that breaks legs. Eccentric loading is the prep nobody trains.',
    read: '6 min',
  },
  {
    date: 'Nov 02, 2025',
    tag: 'Type 1',
    title: 'A CGM, a kettlebell, and the order of things.',
    body:
      'When you combine resistance and aerobic work, the order matters. What the CGM showed me about three months of careful experimenting with sequence.',
    read: '10 min',
  },
];
---
<Layout title="Field Notes — Matt Sanford" screenLabel="05 Field Notes" active="notes">
  <section class="pagehead">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">Field Notes</span>
      <h1>Slow writing about strength, sleep, and the long game.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Quality over frequency. Most months there's nothing new. When there
        is, it lives here.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <article style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: 1.1fr 1fr; gap: 56px; align-items:end; padding-bottom: 64px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
        <div>
          <div class="meta" style="display:flex; gap: 14px; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--granite); margin-bottom: 18px;">
            <span>Featured</span><span>·</span><span>Methodology</span><span>·</span><span>Apr 2026</span>
          </div>
          <h2 style="font-size: clamp(36px, 4.4vw, 56px); line-height: 1.05; max-width: 18ch;">
            What a CHEK assessment actually looks like.
          </h2>
          <p style="margin-top: 24px; color: var(--granite); font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.6; max-width: 50ch;">
            The intake takes ninety minutes. We start with breathing and end
            with the squat. Here's why that order matters more than most
            clients expect — and what you'll actually leave with.
          </p>
          <a href="#" class="btn btn-ghost" style="margin-top: 24px;">Read · 6 min <span class="arrow">→</span></a>
        </div>
        <div
          class="photo-frame wide"
          style="aspect-ratio: 5/4; background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518611012118-696072aa579a?w=1400&q=80&auto=format&fit=crop')"
        >
          <div class="label">Studio · The first ten minutes</div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <div style="margin-top: 80px;">
        <div style="display:flex; align-items:baseline; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 36px; padding-bottom: 16px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
          <h2 style="font-size: 32px;">All notes</h2>
          <div style="display: flex; gap: 18px; font-size: 13px; letter-spacing: 0.12em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--granite);">
            <a href="#" style="color: var(--forest-deep); border-bottom: 1px solid currentColor; padding-bottom: 2px;">All</a>
            <a href="#">Methodology</a>
            <a href="#">Type 1</a>
            <a href="#">Hiking</a>
            <a href="#">Recovery</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div style="display: grid; gap: 0;">
          {posts.map((p) => (
            <a href="#" style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: 140px 1fr 200px; gap: 32px; align-items:start; padding: 28px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);">
              <span style="font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; color: var(--granite-soft); font-size: 15px;">{p.date}</span>
              <div>
                <span class="tag" style="margin-bottom: 12px;">{p.tag}</span>
                <h3 style="margin-top: 12px; font-size: 28px; line-height: 1.18; max-width: 28ch;">{p.title}</h3>
                <p style="color: var(--granite); margin-top: 10px; font-size: 16px; max-width: 56ch;">{p.body}</p>
              </div>
              <span style="text-align: right; font-size: 13px; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--forest);">Read · {p.read} →</span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section style="background: var(--paper-warm);">
    <div class="container" style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 56px; align-items:center;">
      <div>
        <span class="eyebrow">Subscribe</span>
        <h2 style="margin-top: 14px;">Get the next note when there's one to send.</h2>
        <p style="margin-top: 18px; color: var(--granite); font-size: 17px; max-width: 50ch;">
          Most months there's nothing. When there's something worth saying,
          it shows up in your inbox. No tracking pixels, no upsells, no
          automated drip sequences. Just the note.
        </p>
      </div>
      <form class="form" style="max-width: none;">
        <div class="field">
          <label>Email</label>
          <input type="email" placeholder="you@somewhere" />
        </div>
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" style="justify-self:start;">
          Subscribe <span class="arrow">→</span>
        </button>
      </form>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
